$X \longrightarrow Y ; \Delta \mathrm{H}=-135 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$, $\mathrm{E}_a=150 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}$ For an exothermic reaction
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \mathrm{E}_{a(\mathrm{~F} . \mathrm{R} .)}=\Delta \mathrm{H}+\mathrm{E}_{a(\mathrm{~B} . \mathrm{R} .)}^{\prime} \\
& 150=-135+\mathrm{E}_{a a \text { (B.R.) }}^{\prime} \\
& \mathrm{E}_{a(\mathrm{~B} . \mathrm{R})}^{\prime}=285 \mathrm{~kJ} / \mathrm{mol}
\end{aligned}
$$

Energy required for $1 \mathrm{Cl}_2$ molecule $=\frac{242 \times 10^3}{\mathrm{~N}_{\mathrm{A}}}$ Joules.
This energy is contained in photon of wavelength ' $\lambda$ '.
$$
\begin{aligned}
& \frac{\mathrm{hc}}{\lambda}=\mathrm{E} \Rightarrow \frac{6.626 \times 10^{-34} \times 3 \times 10^8}{\lambda}=\frac{242 \times 10^3}{6.022 \times 10^{23}} \\
& \lambda=4947 Å \approx 494 \mathrm{~nm}
\end{aligned}
$$
